column2: Title of object. Transcribe as found, construct a descriptive title if no title exists.
column4: Content-specific note. For other notes, use public_note.
column5: Date of creation. Use description if date is unclear/uncertain (i.e. approximate 1890, 1890?, or [1890] if the date is inferred). If there are no dates, use 'Unknown'.
column7: Title of the archival/physical collection the object belongs to. Take title from SCOUT if exists.
column8: SCOUT identifier for the archival/physical collection.
column10: Enter box/folder, call number or other locational information for the physical object. Optional.
column11: Enter information about the physical extent of an item including dimensions. Specify the unit of measurement. Optional.
column13: Code 'eng' for English, 'zxx' for objects with no linguistic content.
column14: A geographic place represented/depicted in the content of the object. For where the object originated, use place_of_origin.
column15: Repeated subject geographic field to show how to repeat.
column18: A named entity (person or organization) represented/depicted in the content of the object. For an entity that created/produced the object, use name. Format names as so: Last Name, First Name Middle Name, Life Dates. Include as much as possible. Example: Smith, John Quincy, 1700-1800
column20: The title of the digital project/collection.
column21: Used the LCNAF form of the repository (the place the physical item is held) name.
column22: Choose from drop down.
column23: Any non-content specific notes about the object (i.e. notes that don't fit into abstract).
column24: repeated column for more notes.
